    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, **Corbin Carroll** stands as the definitive anchor of the lineup with an elite score of 87.14. He draws a highly favorable matchup against Painter, whose 4.82 xERA suggests a prime opportunity for **Corbin Carroll** to leverage his speed\u2014a critical priority given our focus on the scarcest category, SB. Similarly, **Brice Turang** earns a strong endorsement at 66.23; despite the presence of a catcher with a 1.89s pop time, the combination of his leadoff spot and a soft matchup against Littell keeps him well above the 60-point threshold. **Trevor Story** also presents an intriguing high-upside play at 64.07, as the combination of a slow opposing delivery and favorable wind conditions provides the necessary runway for him to steal a base against Pallante.\n\nWhile the optimizer favored our top starters, the decision to bench **Zach McKinstry** was the closest call of the morning. His score of 49.24 was bolstered by a high potential for stolen bases against Alcantara, but he ultimately couldn't displace the higher-floor profiles of **Seiya Suzuki** or **Tyler Soderstrom**. We are also keeping a watchful eye on **Mickey Moniak**, who boasts a strong 64.99 score thanks to a prime #3 slotting, though he carries a 39% rain risk that could compromise his game cap utilization. Meanwhile, **James Wood** remains in the lineup despite a tough draw against the elite Woodruff (2.90 xERA), as his speed-centric profile and leadoff positioning maintain his utility. We will monitor the status of **Austin Riley** and **Josh Naylor** closely; their \"Lineup Pending\" status necessitates a final check before first pitch, but their projected impacts currently warrant their inclusion over the rest of our bench depth, including **Max Muncy** and **Jose Caballero**, who lacked the requisite matchup efficiency to justify a start today.",
